The UV–vis absorption spectrum of chitosan derived CQD, CdTe@MPA and CQD-CdTe are presented in Fig. S4. In the absorption spectrum of CQD a broad band in the range 249 nm–319 nm accounts for π-π* and n-π* transitions. CdTe shows a broad absorption band at 619 nm as a result to electronic transition from V-band to C-band. Interestingly, when CQD is added to CdTe QD the absorption band at 619 nm disappeared (Fig. S6). In the PL spectrum of CQD-CdTe shows two bands at 430 nm and 632 nm originated from CQD and CdTe respectively. With an increase in the concentration of CQD in the CQD-CdTe solution the intensity of the emission band at 632 nm decreases and at certain concentration of CQD the emission band at 632 nm entirely vanished (Fig. 2
                        ). The emission intensity of the excited state CdTe could be supressed as a consequence of FRET or PET. At the same time, the absorption spectrum of CQD and emission spectrum of CdTe do not merge (Fig. S5), which does not support the possibility for FRET between CdTe and CQD. On the otherhand, it has been previously reported that CQD efficiently acts as a photo excited electron acceptor from semiconductor quantum dots thus quenching the absorption and emission of quantum dots [37–39]. A similar kind of mechanism can be proposed for chitosan driven CQD and MPA capped CdTe. The interaction of MPA modified CdTe and chitosan derived CQD is facilitated through hydrogen bonding interaction COOH on CdTe and –NH2 groups of CQD. The formation of CdTe-CQD complex is evidenced from remarkable change in zeta potential of CdTe@MPA from (-27.4 mV) to (−22 mV) in CdTe-CQD. TEM images of the CdTe-CQD pair shows some isolated particles identified as CQD and CdTe. In addition to abundant CQD-CdTe aggregated particles were observed which can be identified at high resolution. Two different lattice spacing d values at 0.28 nm and 0.36 nm have been observed which correspond to [101] of CQD and [111] of CdTe respectively (Fig. 3
                        ). Therefore there is clear evidence that the formation of tightly associated CQD-CdTe pair is responsible for quenching of red emission band (λem=632 nm) of CdTe.

The fluorescence response of CQD-CdTe QDs probe has been investigated by gradual addition of glyphosate to the sensor medium. When glyphosate concentration was increased from 10 nM to 1000 nM, there is remarkable enhancement in the emission intensity of CQD-CdTe at 619 nm. At optimum reaction conditions the increase in emission signal at 619 nm of CQD-CdTe solution in the presence of variable concentrations of glyphosate is presented in Fig. 4
                        a. The change in emission intensity of CQD-CdTe versus glyphosate concentration clearly shows a linear response in the range 0–100 nM with a limit of detection of 2 pM (8 μg/L) (Fig. 4c), as calculated following our previously reported paper [40]. To the best of our knowledge this LOD is the lowest among most of the reported fluorimetric and/or colorimetric sensor for the detection of glyphosate in aqueous medium (Table 1
                        ).
